  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Short-term rental properties have become a common part of the Brisbane inner-east market over the past decade. Whether you have been running an Airbnb as a primary income stream or renting out a spare room while you travel, selling a property that is actively operating as a short-term rental involves some considerations that a standard owner-occupied or long-term tenanted sale does not. Getting these right before you go to market will save you complications during the campaign and at settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do with existing bookings</h2>
      <p>The most immediate practical question when selling an active Airbnb is what happens to bookings already confirmed for dates after your likely settlement. Airbnb bookings are contractual commitments to guests. If you cancel those bookings, Airbnb applies penalties to your host account and guests receive refunds, but you also face reputational damage on the platform. Depending on your listing's cancellation settings, short-notice cancellations may result in significant financial penalties.</p>

      <p>The better approach is to decide early whether you will continue accepting new bookings during your campaign or close off new bookings from the point you commit to selling. Many STR owners stop accepting bookings as soon as they sign with an agent, then honour existing confirmed bookings and allow the pipeline to wind down naturally. This is usually the cleanest path. The precise implication for your settlement date is worth discussing with your solicitor upfront, because confirmed bookings that fall after your settlement date are a complication you want to resolve before contracts are signed, not after.</p>

      <p>If you sell to another investor who intends to continue operating the property as a short-term rental, the transition of platform accounts and existing reviews is worth considering. Airbnb listings, along with accumulated reviews, cannot be transferred between accounts. The buyer would need to start a new listing from scratch. Some vendors mention the property's STR income history in marketing to demonstrate revenue potential, but the listing itself does not transfer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Presenting to owner-occupier versus investor buyers</h2>
      <p>The buyer pool for an Airbnb property in Brisbane's inner east is genuinely mixed. Some buyers will be investors specifically looking for established short-term rental income. Others will be owner-occupiers who have no interest in continuing the STR operation and simply want to live in the property. How you present the property needs to account for both, and getting that balance right influences your result.</p>

      <p>For owner-occupier buyers, a property that has been used for short-term rentals needs to be presented in a way that signals it is well maintained and genuinely liveable, not just optimised for guest turnover. Wear and tear from frequent guest use can accumulate in ways that are less obvious in a long-term tenancy: sofas that have seen hundreds of guests, carpets worn near high-traffic entry points, kitchen items at the end of their life. Addressing these presentation issues before listing is important, because owner-occupier buyers in the inner east are generally discerning and will factor visible wear into their offer.</p>

      <p>For investor buyers, the income history is a relevant data point. A property with a verifiable STR income record in a strong-performing Brisbane inner-east suburb is a meaningful selling point, particularly if the local regulatory environment is favourable. Being able to show consistent occupancy rates and revenue over a 12 to 24 month period is more persuasive than projected income based on comparable listings.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Brisbane council regulations and STR compliance</h2>
      <p>Brisbane City Council applies specific rules to short-term accommodation. Properties offering short-term rental accommodation in low-density residential zones generally require development approval if the activity is a non-hosted arrangement (where the owner does not live on the premises) and the letting is ongoing. Hosted arrangements, where the owner is present, are generally treated differently under the planning scheme.</p>

      <p>If your property has been operating as an unhosted short-term rental in a low-density zone without development approval, this is worth clarifying with your solicitor before you go to market. It is not necessarily a barrier to sale, but it is a disclosure issue and buyers' solicitors may raise it during due diligence. Properties in higher-density zones or with commercial zoning typically face fewer restrictions. Your agent should understand the local regulatory context for your specific address.</p>

      <p>It is also worth noting that body corporate by-laws for units and townhouses sometimes restrict or prohibit short-term rental. If your property is in a body corporate scheme, checking the current by-laws before marketing is essential, as this affects what a buyer can do with the property and therefore how you should frame it in your campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Transitioning from Airbnb mode to sale mode</h2>
      <p>A property that is actively operating as an Airbnb often looks quite different to one being prepared for sale. STR properties are typically furnished and styled for guest comfort, with consumables and linen taking up space, wall art that is generic rather than personal, and furniture that prioritises durability over aesthetics. For a sale campaign, especially if you are targeting owner-occupier buyers, the presentation needs to shift.</p>

      <p>This does not always mean emptying the property of furniture. In many cases, a well-furnished property photographs better than an empty one and helps buyers visualise how the space lives. But it does mean curating what stays and what goes. Remove the operational clutter: spare linen, cleaning supplies stored in visible areas, the welcome folder on the kitchen bench, the lockbox on the front door. Bring in a stylist for a consultation if you are uncertain about what to keep. The cost of half a day with a stylist is modest relative to the impact it can have on photography and buyer perception at inspections.</p>

      <p>Photography for an STR listing is usually optimised for platforms like Airbnb, where the first image needs to compete in a grid view and typically shows the most visually appealing room. Real estate photography has a different set of requirements: it needs to show the property's full layout, its connection to outdoor space, and its sense of scale. Budget for a fresh set of professional photographs taken after you have completed the transition from STR to sale mode. Reusing Airbnb photography in your real estate campaign is a common mistake that costs more than it saves.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The access question during the campaign</h2>
      <p>Running a real estate campaign requires consistent access to the property for open homes, private inspections, and photography. This is straightforward when a property is vacant or owner-occupied, but becomes more complicated when guests are checking in and out during the campaign period.</p>

      <p>If you decide to continue honouring existing bookings during your campaign, coordinate the inspection schedule carefully with your agent. Open homes on days when guests are present are generally not possible, and private inspections need to be arranged around check-in and check-out times. This limits your campaign's flexibility and can reduce buyer access at a time when you want as many qualified buyers through the property as possible. Most STR owners selling in Brisbane's inner east find it easier to wind down the bookings pipeline and run the property vacant during the campaign, accepting the loss of short-term rental income for six to eight weeks in exchange for a cleaner campaign experience.</p>

